=== SLIDE 1: TITLE ===
ITO Rules of Ownership Accountability and Respect (ROAR)
February 2026

=== SLIDE 2: INTRODUCTION ===
CULTURE IS NOT ACCIDENTAL. IT IS DESIGNED.

=== SLIDE 3: INTRODUCTION ===
APPLIES TO EVERYONE, APPLIES EQUALLY.

=== SLIDE 4: HOW TO ROAR ===
The following expectations describe how we show up, work together, and deliver across the Innovation and Transformation Office.

=== SLIDE 5: RULE 1 — SHOW UP WHERE IT MATTERS ===
Visibility builds trust. Strong teams require shared presence.
- Minimum 3 days per week in office
- Be present for critical meetings and university events
- Do not use hybrid work to avoid accountability
- Support colleagues during high-impact moments

=== SLIDE 6: RULE 2 — IF IT WAS DECIDED, WRITE IT DOWN ===
Undocumented decisions create misalignment. Clarity prevents confusion.
- Every decision requires a written summary
- Capture actions, owners, and deadlines
- Clarify who sends the summary
- Ask recipients to confirm or correct

=== SLIDE 7: RULE 3 — THE 24 HOUR RULE ===
Responsiveness signals professionalism. Silence erodes trust.
- Acknowledge emails and calls within 24-48 hours
- Address what you can immediately
- Set expectations for full responses
- Proactively update if delays occur

=== SLIDE 8: RULE 4 — RESPECT THE CLOCK ===
Respect for time is respect for people. Punctuality reflects the discipline.
- Arrive on time to meetings and calls
- Join fully prepared and ready to start
- Inform the organizer if you will be late
- Notify no later than 10 minutes before start time

=== SLIDE 9: RULE 5 — NO LAST-MINUTE SURPRISES ===
Reliability builds credibility. Consistency strengthens trust.
- Do not cancel meetings at the last minute
- Notify participants early
- Provide notice at least one hour in advance
- Reserve no-shows for true emergencies only

=== SLIDE 10: RULE 6 — SAY WHAT YOU WILL DO. DO WHAT YOU SAY ===
Credibility is built on follow-through. Proactive communication preserves trust.
- End meetings with clear commitments
- Honor agreed deadlines
- If at risk, notify early
- Propose a realistic revised timeline

=== SLIDE 11: RULE 7 — ESCALATE EARLY ===
Protect delivery. Avoid surprises. Escalation is professional, not personal.
- Follow up once when inputs are delayed
- Set a new deadline
- If still unresolved, copy your manager
- Surface risks before they become failures

=== SLIDE 12: RULE 8 — CAMERAS ON ===
Presence matters, even virtually. Visibility strengthens connection.
- Keep cameras on during virtual meetings
- Promote engagement and accountability
- Support effective communication
- Turn off only for technical limitations

=== SLIDE 13: RULE 9 — IF IT IS NOT IN THE SYSTEM, IT DOES NOT EXIST ===
Work must be visible to be managed. Transparency protects everyone.
- All requests require a system ticket (e.g. TDx)
- Do not track work via email or chat alone
- Guide stakeholders to submit properly
- Create tickets on their behalf when needed

=== SLIDE 14: RULE 10 — SEE SOMETHING, DO SOMETHING ===
Culture is everyone's responsibility. Accountable sustains excellence.
- Address conflicting behaviors responsibly
- Do not ignore repeated lapses
- Raise concerns early
- Treat accountability as shared responsibility

=== SLIDE 15: RULE 11 — OWN THE DECISION ===
Debate fully. Execute fully. Alignment accelerates execution.
- Accept final decisions, even if not preferred
- Avoid passive resistance or reopening debate
- Act as an ambassador for the chosen direction
- Support implementation with positivity

=== SLIDE 16: RULE 12 — BE A GOOD STEWARD ===
Manage resources as if they were your own. Stewardship protects credibility.
- Spend only where value is clear
- Avoid unnecessary complexity or scope creep
- Optimize contracts, licenses, and vendors
- Be disciplined with travel and discretionary costs

=== SLIDE 17: PERFORMANCE AND ACCOUNTABILITY ===
Expectations are real. Measurable. Enforced.
Adherence to ROAR impacts:
- Performance evaluations
- Professional credibility
- Team effectiveness
- Institutional reputation

=== SLIDE 18: CLOSING ===
We ROAR Together.
Ownership. Accountability. Respect.
